## Mock Interview Reflection 

**Situation**
A few weeks ago, I took part in a mock interview to get a feel for what real job interviews are like. As a Software Engineering student at Cape Peninsula University of Technology in Cape Town, I saw this as a chance to test myself in a more realistic setting and see how well I could talk about my skills and experiences.

**Task**
My aim was to present myself clearly, explain my projects in a way that makes sense, and handle both technical and general questions without getting overwhelmed. I also wanted to see where I might struggle so I could improve before facing real interviews.

**Action**
During the interview, I spoke about the projects on my CV, like the eCommerce system and the student accommodation idea. I explained the technologies I used, such as Java (Spring Boot), React, and PostgreSQL, and focused on what I actually did, especially on the database side.
At times, I felt a bit nervous, which made me pause or overthink some answers. But I tried to stay calm and keep going. After the interview, I thought about what went well and what didn’t, and I paid attention to the feedback I received.

**Result**
The experience showed me that I do understand my work, but I need to get better at explaining it smoothly and confidently. It also helped me realise the importance of practicing how I speak, not just what I know. Since then, I’ve started working on being more confident and structuring my answers better. Overall, the mock interview was really helpful and gave me a clearer idea of how to improve before real opportunities come up.
